{
  "solution": "1) Starting from the given relation for the blackbody peak wavelength: λ_bb ≈ 16 R_SC. For a blackbody spectrum, Wien's displacement law gives λ_max T = b, where b ≈ 2.898 × 10^{-3} m·K. Thus, T_bh = b / λ_bb ≈ b / (16 R_SC). The Schwarzschild radius is R_SC = 2GM_bh / c^2, where G is the gravitational constant and c is the speed of light. Substituting, T_bh ≈ b c^2 / (32 G M_bh). This is the expression for the black hole temperature in terms of its mass and physical constants.\n\n2) For a black hole of mass M_bh = 19.7061 M_⊙, first compute R_SC. Using R_SC,⊙ = 2.952 km for 1 M_⊙, R_SC = (M_bh / M_⊙) × R_SC,⊙ = 19.7061 × 2.952 km = 58.172 km (since 2.952 × 19.7061 = 58.172). Then compute T_bh using T_bh = b / (16 R_SC). With b = 2.898 × 10^{-3} m·K and R_SC = 58.172 × 10^3 m, T_bh = 2.898e-3 / (16 × 58.172e3) = 2.898e-3 / (930.752e3) = 2.898e-3 / 9.30752e5 = 3.114 × 10^{-9} K.",
